00:08:13.740 --> 00:08:18.020
The third barrier--
is that source,

00:08:18.020 --> 00:08:20.670
once you've identified
it, credible?

00:08:20.670 --> 00:08:24.120
For example, does anyone
remember Baghdad Bob back

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:26.400
in the year of Saddam Hussein?

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:28.879
That guy rapidly
lost his credibility.

00:08:28.879 --> 00:08:30.420
He may have had some
at first, and he

00:08:30.420 --> 00:08:33.600
lost it quick to the point
where he became a laughingstock.

00:08:33.600 --> 00:08:36.600
That is what happens when
you lose credibility.

00:08:36.600 --> 00:08:40.200
So news organizations are
very jealously guarding

00:08:40.200 --> 00:08:43.679
their credibility, as, for
example, Dan Rather learned,

00:08:43.679 --> 00:08:50.730
to his discomfort, back in 2003,
when he published information

00:08:50.730 --> 00:08:53.940
that turned out to be
spurious with CBS News'

00:08:53.940 --> 00:08:55.680
imprimatur on it--

00:08:55.680 --> 00:08:58.950
very important for organizations
like CNN, the New York Times

00:08:58.950 --> 00:09:01.410
to maintain their credibility.

00:09:01.410 --> 00:09:03.900
Those news organizations
that handle the extremes

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:07.035
