Now, Chris here reminded me
of a wonderful principle from

00:26:27.520 --> 00:26:29.590
my military days--
defense in depth--

00:26:29.590 --> 00:26:32.100
the idea that you have
multiple layers of defense

00:26:32.100 --> 00:26:33.370
in order to secure something.

00:26:33.370 --> 00:26:39.659
My car was stolen, so I put on
an alarm, and I have LoJack,

00:26:39.659 --> 00:26:41.200
and I have all these
different tricks

00:26:41.200 --> 00:26:43.200
I've pulled to keep it
from being stolen again--

00:26:43.200 --> 00:26:45.700
multiple levels of protection.

00:26:45.700 --> 00:26:47.410
It's the only way to be sure.

00:26:47.410 --> 00:26:50.830
Even then, it's not
foolproof, but it's better.

00:26:50.830 --> 00:26:53.140
And so that's the only
answer I can give you.

00:26:53.140 --> 00:26:55.360
And honestly, one
of things I hope

00:26:55.360 --> 00:26:59.730
is that people will use my
book as a kind of framework

00:26:59.730 --> 00:27:01.660
and that people who are
much smarter than me

00:27:01.660 --> 00:27:06.100
like Noam Chomsky will come in
and say, hey, good start, kid.

00:27:06.100 --> 00:27:07.722
Let's build upon this format.

00:27:07.722 --> 00:27:09.430
Let's build upon this
framework and that,

00:27:09.430 --> 00:27:12.530
by the time they're done,
people like you, for example,

00:27:12.530 --> 00:27:16.490
coming in and telling us about
search engine optimization

00:27:16.490 --> 00:27:19.630
so that a particular
sponsored product comes up

00:27:19.630 --> 00:27:20.950
in your search list first.

00:27:20.950 --> 00:27:23.260
I know nothing about this.

00:27:23.260 --> 00:27:26.090
I need good people like
you to write that chapter.

00:27:26.090 --> 00:27:29.590
And more and more contributors
will come and more and more

00:27:29.590 --> 00:27:32.920
people sharing their experiences
with things like denying access

00:27:32.920 --> 00:27:35.290
so that this firewall can
get stronger and stronger

00:27:35.290 --> 00:27:38.122
and it becomes less and less
associated with me and more

00:27:38.122 --> 00:27:39.580
of the kind of
collaborative effort

00:27:39.580 --> 00:27:41.290
you see at Microsoft,
where they've

00:27:41.290 --> 00:27:44.680
got Windows Defender, written
by many, many more than one

00:27:44.680 --> 00:27:48.110
programmer.

00:27:48.110 --> 00:27:48.700
Next question.

00:27:58.292 --> 00:27:59.750
AUDIENCE: I have
so many questions,

00:27:59.750 --> 00:28:03.140
but one of your
things is evaluating

00:28:03.140 --> 00:28:04.520
the credibility of sources.

00:28:04.520 --> 00:28:06.950
And certainly, in
the last year or so,

00:28:06.950 --> 00:28:11.390
fake news has been very
much one of the topics.

00:28:11.390 --> 00:28:15.200
And there are
various attempts now

00:28:15.200 --> 00:28:18.810
on the part of like Facebook
and other companies,

00:28:18.810 --> 00:28:21.950
including our own,
to try to figure out

00:28:21.950 --> 00:28:23.920
how you might identify this.

00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:27.230
So how can you tell if
a source is credible?

00:28:30.205 --> 00:28:31.580
JACK NOLAN: A very
good question.

00:28:31.580 --> 00:28:36.020
Well, first off, remember
that the political parties are

00:28:36.020 --> 00:28:37.700
trying to ensure brand loyalty.

00:28:37.700 --> 00:28:40.420
If you're one head of
a two-headed duopoly,

00:28:40.420 --> 00:28:42.399
and you know your
product isn't very good,

00:28:42.399 --> 00:28:43.440
what are you going to do?

00:28:43.440 --> 00:28:45.398
You're going to insult
the other guy's product.

00:28:45.398 --> 00:28:48.590
So if you see a
news show or a talk

00:28:48.590 --> 00:28:51.470
show or read an article where
they're just constantly bagging

00:28:51.470 --> 00:28:55.010
on the other side, you know
you're dealing with propaganda.

00:28:55.010 --> 00:28:57.310
Keith Olbermann opens
his mouth, and out pours

00:28:57.310 --> 00:29:02.897
a diatribe against Donald
Trump, or Michael Moore

00:29:02.897 --> 00:29:05.480
opens his mouth and talks about
all the terrible conservatives

00:29:05.480 --> 00:29:06.022
in the world.

00:29:06.022 --> 00:29:08.646
Well, if you're a conservative,
you can naturally take offense,

00:29:08.646 --> 00:29:11.750
but even if you are a liberal,
understand that propaganda

00:29:11.750 --> 00:29:14.145
you agree with is the
most dangerous to you

00:29:14.145 --> 00:29:15.770
and that the true
test of your firewall

00:29:15.770 --> 00:29:18.311
is whether or not it can protect
you from propaganda that you

00:29:18.311 --> 00:29:19.070
agree with.

00:29:19.070 --> 00:29:21.380
And on the other side,
you get Rush Limbaugh

00:29:21.380 --> 00:29:22.940
talking about the
liberals, and you

00:29:22.940 --> 00:29:27.090
get Ann Coulter talking about
how awful the Democrats are

00:29:27.090 --> 00:29:28.970
and how awful Obama is or was.

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:33.220
And yeah, you can know right
there what you're dealing with.

00:29:33.220 --> 00:29:35.450
Now, most of the news sites--

00:29:35.450 --> 00:29:41.540
CNN, US News &amp; World
Report, the BBC--

00:29:41.540 --> 00:29:43.640
these are going to be
reputable because they

00:29:43.640 --> 00:29:46.760
have a lot at stake
with their credibility--

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:49.870
as I said, the
extremes, less so.

00:29:49.870 --> 00:29:52.550
There's a very good website
that I've found I can recommend.

00:29:52.550 --> 00:29:56.180
I have some concerns about it,
but it's called allsides.com.

00:29:56.180 --> 00:30:01.880
And on allsides.com, they have
people reviewing and rating

00:30:01.880 --> 00:30:04.010
the coverage of
various news sources

00:30:04.010 --> 00:30:06.830
and saying where it falls
in the political spectrum.

00:30:06.830 --> 00:30:07.950
That's very useful.

00:30:07.950 --> 00:30:10.940
So they have a page where
you can look at the--

00:30:10.940 --> 00:30:13.710
let's say you find an
article on Huffington Post.

00:30:13.710 --> 00:30:14.989
What's Huffington Post?

00:30:14.989 --> 00:30:16.530
So you look it up,
and lo and behold,

00:30:16.530 --> 00:30:17.738
they're just left of center--

00:30:17.738 --> 00:30:19.460
fine.

00:30:19.460 --> 00:30:22.070
And so you know what
you're dealing with.

00:30:22.070 --> 00:30:27.200
And they present news stories
from all across the spectrum.

00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:29.810
So if you have an interest
in a particular story,

00:30:29.810 --> 00:30:35.300
you can see everybody's take on
it and everybody's spin on it--

00:30:35.300 --> 00:30:36.500
very useful website.

00:30:36.500 --> 00:30:38.630
I have some concerns
about their rating system,

00:30:38.630 --> 00:30:41.619
but all in all, valuable.

00:30:41.619 --> 00:30:43.160
If you're looking
at motion pictures,

00:30:43.160 --> 00:30:45.696
I did find a very
good site called--

00:30:45.696 --> 00:30:48.250
oh, gosh, what was this thing?

00:30:48.250 --> 00:30:49.250
I'll have to look it up.

00:30:49.250 --> 00:30:50.840
But anyway, this
website mentioned

00:30:50.840 --> 00:30:56.540
commercialism, consumerism
in its review of movies--

00:30:56.540 --> 00:30:58.340
very good.

00:30:58.340 --> 00:31:01.760
I think we need websites that
will list the amount of product

00:31:01.760 --> 00:31:05.060
placement from no noticeable
to substantial to Michael Bay

00:31:05.060 --> 00:31:07.910
was feeding on pleasant
habits that month

00:31:07.910 --> 00:31:10.910
and will tell us in advance
before we go to see it

00:31:10.910 --> 00:31:13.310
because they're very good
about slipping these product

00:31:13.310 --> 00:31:17.210
placements in there in a
way that you won't notice.

00:31:17.210 --> 00:31:21.140
And so I forget the
name of the website,

00:31:21.140 --> 00:31:22.550
but I'll get back
to you on that.

00:31:22.550 --> 00:31:25.760
So these are very
useful resources

00:31:25.760 --> 00:31:29.826
that are available if
you're looking for them.

00:31:29.826 --> 00:31:30.450
Does that help?

00:31:32.961 --> 00:31:33.460
Yes, sir.

00:31:41.187 --> 00:31:43.520
AUDIENCE: One thing you said
that kind of surprised me--

00:31:43.520 --> 00:31:47.040
you characterized kind
of the state propaganda

00:31:47.040 --> 00:31:49.820
as the big brother
and the commercial one

00:31:49.820 --> 00:31:50.800
as the little brother.

00:31:50.800 --> 00:31:52.100
It kind of seems odd.

00:31:52.100 --> 00:31:54.470
I think it looks like
way, way more money

00:31:54.470 --> 00:31:59.110
is put into the
commercial propaganda,

00:31:59.110 --> 00:32:05.450
and also the
political propaganda--

00:32:05.450 --> 00:32:08.680
there is somebody who
has as much interest in,

00:32:08.680 --> 00:32:12.560
who also has the resources,
in kind of countering that.

00:32:12.560 --> 00:32:15.200
But in the case of
commercial propaganda,

00:32:15.200 --> 00:32:18.080
where the main message of just
about every commercial that you

00:32:18.080 --> 00:32:23.540
see is that, if you buy my crap,
then you will be loved, right?

00:32:23.540 --> 00:32:29.880
That's the underlying message of
just about any commercial ever.

00:32:29.880 --> 00:32:34.449
Yeah, but then there's
so much little--

00:32:34.449 --> 00:32:36.490
I mean, of course, there
are people who tell you,

00:32:36.490 --> 00:32:39.170
no, no, that's not
what's important.

00:32:39.170 --> 00:32:40.400
They are out there.

00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:43.730
But the amount of exposure that
they can cause to you, I mean,

00:32:43.730 --> 00:32:45.380
they're much smaller.

00:32:45.380 --> 00:32:48.800
So I mean, it would seem to
me it's the other way around.

00:32:48.800 --> 00:32:51.075
The political one is
the little brother.

00:32:51.075 --> 00:32:52.950
JACK NOLAN: Well, you
make a very good point.

00:32:52.950 --> 00:32:55.940
And I agree that,
certainly, the corporations

00:32:55.940 --> 00:32:57.860
tend to be investing
more money, and there

00:32:57.860 --> 00:33:00.470
are fewer voices refuting them.

00:33:00.470 --> 00:33:02.720
One of them would be, for
example, Buddhism-- the idea

00:33:02.720 --> 00:33:05.451
of abjuring materialism.

00:33:05.451 --> 00:33:06.950
I've often thought
that, if Buddhism

00:33:06.950 --> 00:33:08.840
were to become the
major religion,

00:33:08.840 --> 00:33:10.520
that our entire
economy would collapse.

00:33:10.520 --> 00:33:17.390
Anyway, I was really
speaking more in terms of--

00:33:17.390 --> 00:33:19.920
well, I created a Venn
diagram for the book,

00:33:19.920 --> 00:33:21.920
which I wish I had brought
with me as a slide.

00:33:21.920 --> 00:33:27.470
But the idea is that advertising
is a subset of propaganda,

00:33:27.470 --> 00:33:34.640
so purist propaganda you find
in state-sponsored propaganda

00:33:34.640 --> 00:33:36.990
like you'd find, say, in
North Korea or the kind

00:33:36.990 --> 00:33:38.990
that you'd see coming
from the political parties

00:33:38.990 --> 00:33:40.960
during election seasons.

00:33:40.960 --> 00:33:47.120
The subset called
advertising is defined

00:33:47.120 --> 00:33:52.220
as any message that directly
serves the economic needs

00:33:52.220 --> 00:33:53.600
of the sender.

00:33:53.600 --> 00:33:57.080
And so you see, advertising is
a subset of the larger rubric

00:33:57.080 --> 00:33:58.220
of propaganda.

00:33:58.220 --> 00:34:01.060
And to my way of thinking, it's
much the less interesting one.

00:34:01.060 --> 00:34:05.660
I mean, I feel that we have
that we've inundated ourselves

00:34:05.660 --> 00:34:08.690
with advertising to the
point of saturation,

00:34:08.690 --> 00:34:10.580
and I find it depressing.

00:34:10.580 --> 00:34:13.699
But I don't find it as
dangerous as the kind of thing

00:34:13.699 --> 00:34:16.040
that we're seeing
now with fake news,

00:34:16.040 --> 00:34:18.590
and that's why I'm so alarmed.

00:34:18.590 --> 00:34:22.760
And honestly, when I wrote
my book back in 2015,

00:34:22.760 --> 00:34:26.210
I had no idea that,
suddenly, fake news

00:34:26.210 --> 00:34:28.360
and alternative facts--

00:34:28.360 --> 00:34:31.070
a phrase designed
to make Orwell spin

00:34:31.070 --> 00:34:33.679
in his coffin like a dervish--

00:34:33.679 --> 00:34:37.250
that these would
become front page news

00:34:37.250 --> 00:34:39.880
and would be dominating
the airwaves.

00:34:39.880 --> 00:34:42.210
Really, in some ways, I
feel like I was pressing,

00:34:42.210 --> 00:34:43.672
and I'm very grateful.

00:34:43.672 --> 00:34:45.130
I wish things had
gone differently.

00:34:45.130 --> 00:34:48.650
Anyway, so that's why
I feel that advertising

00:34:48.650 --> 00:34:51.409
can be thought of as a little
brother to the larger scale

00:34:51.409 --> 00:34:52.310
propaganda.

00:34:52.310 --> 00:34:53.750
But you're right.

00:34:53.750 --> 00:34:56.960
More funds go into advertising--

00:34:56.960 --> 00:34:59.180
what we think of as
commercials-- than

00:34:59.180 --> 00:35:00.630
go into political campaigns.

00:35:00.630 --> 00:35:03.990
But political campaigns
are significant.

00:35:03.990 --> 00:35:07.172
I know that, in a book
"The Assault on Reason"

00:35:07.172 --> 00:35:09.380
written by Al Gore-- and I
cannot recommend this book

00:35:09.380 --> 00:35:11.734
because Al Gore is very
partisan-- however,

00:35:11.734 --> 00:35:14.150
he did write something that I
think is important for every

00:35:14.150 --> 00:35:16.280
American to understand.

00:35:16.280 --> 00:35:18.380
He wrote that-- and
he's a senator, mind,

00:35:18.380 --> 00:35:20.960
so he's putting his credibility
on the line by saying this--

00:35:20.960 --> 00:35:24.140
during the build up to
the second intervention

00:35:24.140 --> 00:35:25.154
Desert Storm--

00:35:25.154 --> 00:35:26.570
second intervention
in Iraq-- this

00:35:26.570 --> 00:35:30.560
would be under George W. Bush,
not Desert Storm, excuse me.

00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:33.380
When the Capitol
dome should have

00:35:33.380 --> 00:35:39.000
been ringing with extensive
debate, most of the senators

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:40.560
were absent.

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:42.330
They weren't there
debating whether or not

00:35:42.330 --> 00:35:44.190
our country should go to
war, which is, I think,

00:35:44.190 --> 00:35:45.398
one of their major functions.

00:35:45.398 --> 00:35:50.340
No, they were out soliciting
funds for their re-election

00:35:50.340 --> 00:35:51.690
campaigns.

00:35:51.690 --> 00:35:55.060
And what are they buying
with these solicited funds?

00:35:55.060 --> 00:35:57.000
Propaganda.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.700
They're buying commercial spots,
and they're buying buttons,

00:35:59.700 --> 00:36:02.760
and they're buying posters.

00:36:02.760 --> 00:36:06.720
So yes, propaganda,
once again, shows itself

00:36:06.720 --> 00:36:09.840
as being one of our
society's major problems.

00:36:09.840 --> 00:36:14.040
And if we take it upon
ourselves to make ourselves

00:36:14.040 --> 00:36:16.110
more resistant to propaganda--

00:36:16.110 --> 00:36:19.330
mind, there's no such
things invulnerability.

00:36:19.330 --> 00:36:20.970
I'm as well as they
come in this field,

00:36:20.970 --> 00:36:22.510
and I'm not invulnerable.

00:36:26.652 --> 00:36:30.480
If we take it upon ourselves to
make ourselves more resistant--

00:36:30.480 --> 00:36:31.380
and who knows?

00:36:31.380 --> 00:36:33.480
Maybe all these senators
and representatives

00:36:33.480 --> 00:36:36.390
will actually try other means
to get themselves re-elected

00:36:36.390 --> 00:36:40.870
like doing their jobs well.

00:36:40.870 --> 00:36:43.560
But that's why, I
feel, that advertising

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:45.120
should be considered
a little brother

00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:46.680
to big brother propaganda.

00:36:46.680 --> 00:36:51.647
Also frankly, big brother
propaganda came first.

00:36:51.647 --> 00:36:52.230
Next question.

00:36:55.415 --> 00:36:59.710
Now, fair disclosure-- I'd like
to introduce Abbie Melideo.

00:36:59.710 --> 00:37:04.110
Abbie Melideo studied
profiling with the FBI

00:37:04.110 --> 00:37:06.330
and looked over the
psychological side of my book

00:37:06.330 --> 00:37:07.590
when it was in development.

00:37:07.590 --> 00:37:10.410
She also designed
this spiffy cover.

00:37:10.410 --> 00:37:11.820
ABBIE MELIDEO: Thank you, Jack.

00:37:11.820 --> 00:37:16.440
OK, as a renegade
professional propagandist,

00:37:16.440 --> 00:37:19.650
what can you do, if you
can do anything directly,

00:37:19.650 --> 00:37:21.325
to target the fake news problem?

00:37:25.560 --> 00:37:28.800
JACK NOLAN: In my
opinion, all we can do

00:37:28.800 --> 00:37:33.300
is to put the firewall out
there like Windows Defender

00:37:33.300 --> 00:37:36.600
or Adblock or any
other program that we

00:37:36.600 --> 00:37:41.400
use to protect our computers
from outside tampering.

00:37:41.400 --> 00:37:42.780
But this is one for our minds.

00:37:42.780 --> 00:37:46.996
We didn't take it seriously,
and in our arrogance,

00:37:46.996 --> 00:37:48.120
we thought, no, we're fine.

00:37:48.120 --> 00:37:49.328
Propaganda doesn't affect us.

00:37:49.328 --> 00:37:53.850
Yes, it does as any successful
ad man will tell you.

00:37:53.850 --> 00:37:56.580
And Putin exploited that--

00:37:56.580 --> 00:37:58.260
not good.

00:37:58.260 --> 00:38:00.870
I think we need to be
teaching this material

00:38:00.870 --> 00:38:02.950
at the high school
level, as I said.

00:38:02.950 --> 00:38:06.900
I think we need to be
teaching Aristotelian logic

00:38:06.900 --> 00:38:10.527
and argumentative logic at
the high school senior level.

00:38:10.527 --> 00:38:12.360
And so that's why I'm
working my friend Doug

00:38:12.360 --> 00:38:13.860
King as a high school teacher.

00:38:13.860 --> 00:38:17.610
I'm hoping to turn this
into what's called a module,

00:38:17.610 --> 00:38:21.960
like four-week standard module
and a two-week fast track

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:25.690
so that this can be available
to history teachers,

00:38:25.690 --> 00:38:29.549
social studies teachers, and
English teachers, and in fact,

00:38:29.549 --> 00:38:30.465
anybody who wants it--

00:38:30.465 --> 00:38:32.760
it'll fit into anything
besides math, I guess--

00:38:32.760 --> 00:38:36.540
so that this material can
be taught to our students.

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:40.330
I think, as I said before, the
buck stops with us this time.

00:38:40.330 --> 00:38:43.470
The legislature is
not going to help us,

00:38:43.470 --> 00:38:45.930
and the police
force can't help us.

00:38:45.930 --> 00:38:47.132
It's up to us.

00:38:47.132 --> 00:38:49.090
ABBIE MELIDEO: So are
you saying it's too late?

00:38:49.090 --> 00:38:51.725
We have to start early
when they're kids?

00:38:51.725 --> 00:38:52.350
JACK NOLAN: No.

00:38:52.350 --> 00:38:53.310
No, I'm not.

00:38:53.310 --> 00:38:55.110
I think that anybody
can be taught

00:38:55.110 --> 00:38:58.530
and can teach themselves, when
exposed to the right material,

00:38:58.530 --> 00:39:00.990
to think like a propagandist.

00:39:00.990 --> 00:39:02.940
Ray Bradbury once
said, if you can't

00:39:02.940 --> 00:39:05.490
find the book that you
want in the library,

00:39:05.490 --> 00:39:07.200
sit down and write it.

00:39:07.200 --> 00:39:09.060
Well, I looked around--

00:39:09.060 --> 00:39:12.210
Edward Bernays, Gustave Le Bon--

00:39:12.210 --> 00:39:13.930
God help us-- "The
Devil's Diaries"--

00:39:13.930 --> 00:39:18.240
I had to wade that Parisians
sewer to write my book.

00:39:18.240 --> 00:39:20.310
And now I've brought
his nuggets of wisdom

00:39:20.310 --> 00:39:21.630
for you so you don't have to.

00:39:21.630 --> 00:39:24.290
You're welcome.

00:39:24.290 --> 00:39:26.040
It was hard reading.

00:39:26.040 --> 00:39:32.430
But no primer existed, no
propaganda for dummies.

00:39:32.430 --> 00:39:34.410
And so I thought, I'm
going to write this.

00:39:34.410 --> 00:39:37.230
I created a primer based
upon my military training

00:39:37.230 --> 00:39:39.360
to say, OK, here's a framework.

00:39:39.360 --> 00:39:40.620
We can build on this.

00:39:40.620 --> 00:39:42.120
We can make this work.

00:39:42.120 --> 00:39:43.620
It's not too late.

00:39:43.620 --> 00:39:46.860
We can give people the
special sunglasses.

00:39:46.860 --> 00:39:51.010
We can show people
how I see the world.

00:39:51.010 --> 00:39:52.790
And I think that it will be--

00:39:52.790 --> 00:39:54.850
well, it won't be
absolute protection,

00:39:54.850 --> 00:39:58.380
but it will be one extra layer
of protection, one more barrier

00:39:58.380 --> 00:40:01.230
to prevent outside influence.

00:40:01.230 --> 00:40:05.340
And that makes us more free
as individuals, as well

00:40:05.340 --> 00:40:05.940
as a nation.

00:40:12.310 --> 00:40:14.560
ABBIE MELIDEO: Thank you.

00:40:14.560 --> 00:40:17.180
AUDIENCE: I had one
other question myself,

00:40:17.180 --> 00:40:21.640
which was how can we use
propaganda in our own lives

00:40:21.640 --> 00:40:24.939
for our own benefit in a
positive way, not an evil way?

00:40:24.939 --> 00:40:26.730
JACK NOLAN: Oh, I'm so
glad you asked that.

00:40:29.680 --> 00:40:32.335
Let me give you some of
my favorite examples.

00:40:35.680 --> 00:40:38.080
The tools of propaganda
are more properly called

00:40:38.080 --> 00:40:40.270
the art of persuasion.

00:40:40.270 --> 00:40:43.199
Now, we use persuasion
all the time.

00:40:43.199 --> 00:40:44.740
If the tools of the
art of persuasion

00:40:44.740 --> 00:40:49.136
are not used to directly
benefit you as the sender,

00:40:49.136 --> 00:40:51.190
well, then they're
not propaganda.

00:40:51.190 --> 00:40:52.510
But you can use these tools.

00:40:52.510 --> 00:40:55.240
For example, I mentioned
using cigarettes and alcohol

00:40:55.240 --> 00:40:58.300
in Casablanca to
enforce a new norm.

00:40:58.300 --> 00:40:59.980
Well, let's look
at people who've

00:40:59.980 --> 00:41:02.590
used that tool in other ways.

00:41:02.590 --> 00:41:05.460
1967-- Bill Shatner's
"Star Trek"--

00:41:05.460 --> 00:41:07.540
everybody remember that?

00:41:07.540 --> 00:41:11.410
Well, you have a
milieu of the Mad Men,

00:41:11.410 --> 00:41:14.140
where Caucasian
males run everything

00:41:14.140 --> 00:41:16.180
and the women are consigned
to the switchboards

00:41:16.180 --> 00:41:19.480
and the African-Americans
are consigned to the waiters.

00:41:19.480 --> 00:41:23.140
And they come home from
that exhausting world, where

00:41:23.140 --> 00:41:25.360
the Democratic National
Committee are literally

00:41:25.360 --> 00:41:28.630
punch fests, and they
sit down and they

00:41:28.630 --> 00:41:33.280
see this new workplace-- the
bridge of the enterprise, where

00:41:33.280 --> 00:41:35.740
an African-American
woman and an Asian man

00:41:35.740 --> 00:41:38.380
and an alien and a Russian
are all working together

00:41:38.380 --> 00:41:39.040
in harmony.

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:41.123
And they're there because
of their accomplishments

00:41:41.123 --> 00:41:43.420
not because of their race.

00:41:43.420 --> 00:41:45.700
That was an inspiring
new message back then.

00:41:45.700 --> 00:41:48.892
I mean, it seems kind of
quaint now because, that is,

00:41:48.892 --> 00:41:50.350
we've kind of made
that a reality--

00:41:50.350 --> 00:41:51.370
terrific.

00:41:51.370 --> 00:41:53.530
But Gene Roddenberry
and Gene Coon

00:41:53.530 --> 00:41:56.660
gave us this vision of a future.

00:41:56.660 --> 00:41:58.870
Another example--
there was a man

00:41:58.870 --> 00:42:01.960
who was a veteran of
the Pacific theater.

00:42:01.960 --> 00:42:04.570
And then he went into
ad work, writing jingles

00:42:04.570 --> 00:42:08.710
and so forth, and he got so
sick of it just like I did.

00:42:08.710 --> 00:42:11.320
So he began writing
TV shows, and he was

00:42:11.320 --> 00:42:13.870
known as TV's angry young man.

00:42:13.870 --> 00:42:15.490
And after writing
some serious shows

00:42:15.490 --> 00:42:16.990
and getting them
rejected by the censors,

00:42:16.990 --> 00:42:17.948
he says, you know what?

00:42:17.948 --> 00:42:20.380
I'm going to make a fantasy
show because fantasy shows

00:42:20.380 --> 00:42:22.002
the censors don't care about.

00:42:22.002 --> 00:42:23.710
And there's a fabulous
interview with him

00:42:23.710 --> 00:42:26.980
with Mike Wallace, where Mike
Wallace comes down on him

00:42:26.980 --> 00:42:28.530
for writing for a
lightweight genre.

00:42:28.530 --> 00:42:29.821
What are you doing selling out?

00:42:29.821 --> 00:42:31.320
No, I'm not selling out.

00:42:31.320 --> 00:42:33.430
I'm making something amazing.

00:42:33.430 --> 00:42:35.890
Well, that creator
was named Rod Serling,

00:42:35.890 --> 00:42:38.800
and I'm sure you all
remember "The Twilight Zone."

00:42:38.800 --> 00:42:40.190
Now, "The Twilight Zone"--

00:42:40.190 --> 00:42:41.920
there's no interpreting.

00:42:41.920 --> 00:42:43.322
He dominates his audience.

00:42:43.322 --> 00:42:45.280
He tells you exactly what
he wants you to think

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:46.570
by the end of that show.

00:42:46.570 --> 00:42:50.380
That's the mechanism of
manipulation at work.

00:42:50.380 --> 00:42:53.680
This guy was using those tools
that he learned at advertising

00:42:53.680 --> 00:42:56.230
to channel you to his
preconceived conclusions

00:42:56.230 --> 00:42:57.940
all the way.

00:42:57.940 --> 00:42:59.740
And God bless him for it--

00:42:59.740 --> 00:43:01.750
really good stuff.

00:43:01.750 --> 00:43:04.270
Norman Lear-- "All
in the Family"--

00:43:04.270 --> 00:43:06.404
showing us Archie Bunker.

00:43:06.404 --> 00:43:07.570
Do you want to be like this?

00:43:07.570 --> 00:43:08.350
No, you don't.

00:43:08.350 --> 00:43:10.360
Then don't think like him--

00:43:10.360 --> 00:43:11.420
good stuff.

00:43:11.420 --> 00:43:14.870
And we see this continuing
in the modern era.

00:43:14.870 --> 00:43:17.502
We see television shows
that are put together

00:43:17.502 --> 00:43:19.210
and motion pictures
that are put together

00:43:19.210 --> 00:43:22.420
by liked people, who
have an idea of what

00:43:22.420 --> 00:43:26.350
they'd like the world to
be and want to promote it.

00:43:26.350 --> 00:43:28.600
Most recently, and
please don't laugh,

00:43:28.600 --> 00:43:30.520
I'm very fond of
"My Little Pony"--

00:43:30.520 --> 00:43:32.080
the recent revision.

00:43:32.080 --> 00:43:33.760
Lauren Faust is the
name of the creator,

00:43:33.760 --> 00:43:36.430
and she created a lovely vision
of the world as it should be.

00:43:36.430 --> 00:43:39.940
And if you dismiss the
unicorns and the pegasuses,

00:43:39.940 --> 00:43:41.680
it's a really lovely vision.

00:43:41.680 --> 00:43:43.610
So yes, this is
happening even today.

00:43:43.610 --> 00:43:47.350
That's how you use
propaganda for the best.

00:43:47.350 --> 00:43:50.470
Just remember, your objective
is not to profit yourself.

00:43:50.470 --> 00:43:55.960
Your objective is to elevate
and ennoble your audience.

00:43:55.960 --> 00:44:00.280
Hold on to that vision,
and you can't go wrong.

00:44:00.280 --> 00:44:02.140
SPEAKER: Anything else?

00:44:02.140 --> 00:44:04.000
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:05.010
SPEAKER: Oh, yeah.

00:44:05.010 --> 00:44:08.004
JACK NOLAN: Please, please.

00:44:08.004 --> 00:44:09.920
AUDIENCE: Well, since
you brought up Goebbels,

00:44:09.920 --> 00:44:15.250
do you have any thoughts
on his big lie hypothesis?

00:44:15.250 --> 00:44:18.160
JACK NOLAN: Oh, there's
one of my favorites.

00:44:18.160 --> 00:44:19.970
It's a damned lie.

00:44:19.970 --> 00:44:22.210
It doesn't exist.

00:44:22.210 --> 00:44:24.340
The myth of the big lie
comes from a passage

00:44:24.340 --> 00:44:29.290
in "Mein Kampf" in which
old Schicklgruber accused

00:44:29.290 --> 00:44:32.890
the other side of using big lie.

00:44:32.890 --> 00:44:36.070
And there's also a passage
in one of the motion pictures

00:44:36.070 --> 00:44:38.300
that Goebbels created called--

00:44:38.300 --> 00:44:40.960
not "Jud Suss"--
which one is it--

00:44:40.960 --> 00:44:45.100
anyway, one of his
propaganda stories,

00:44:45.100 --> 00:44:49.330
where one of his antagonists,
who's, of course, Jewish,

00:44:49.330 --> 00:44:51.790
starts talking about big lie.

00:44:51.790 --> 00:44:56.020
And the English accuse the
Germans of using big lie.

00:44:56.020 --> 00:45:01.000
I read the entirety of Joseph
Goebbels personal diaries.

00:45:05.470 --> 00:45:07.570
Never once did I catch him
bragging about actually

00:45:07.570 --> 00:45:09.460
using the big lie.

00:45:09.460 --> 00:45:10.630
And he gloats.

00:45:10.630 --> 00:45:12.660
Trust me, he gloats.

00:45:12.660 --> 00:45:15.830
No, I didn't catch him once
gloating about using it,

00:45:15.830 --> 00:45:18.260
and I can tell you that
it's not a principle that

00:45:18.260 --> 00:45:21.860
is taught at the USAJFK
Special Warfare Center

00:45:21.860 --> 00:45:24.420
and School for Psychological
Operations and Warfare.

00:45:24.420 --> 00:45:25.670
It's simply not taught.

00:45:25.670 --> 00:45:27.530
It doesn't work.

00:45:27.530 --> 00:45:30.200
While we're on things
that don't work,

00:45:30.200 --> 00:45:34.360
and we're debunking myths,
subliminal advertising

00:45:34.360 --> 00:45:36.330
from Dr. Joseph
Goebbels himself--

00:45:36.330 --> 00:45:42.050
propaganda that is not perceived
is not propaganda at all.

00:45:42.050 --> 00:45:44.030
Excuse me.

00:45:44.030 --> 00:45:45.830
If you can't perceive
it, it doesn't work.

00:45:45.830 --> 00:45:48.350
Now, can it trigger somebody
sitting in the audience

00:45:48.350 --> 00:45:50.150
who's already hungry
and who likes popcorn

00:45:50.150 --> 00:45:52.840
to go and buy some popcorn?

00:45:52.840 --> 00:45:53.870
Maybe.

00:45:53.870 --> 00:45:58.790
Can it persuade large groups of
people the way propaganda does?

00:45:58.790 --> 00:45:59.720
Absolutely not.

00:45:59.720 --> 00:46:03.155
If it could, my job would
have been a lot easier.

00:46:03.155 --> 00:46:04.460
Does that answer your question?

00:46:07.110 --> 00:46:08.370
Do we have anymore?

00:46:08.370 --> 00:46:11.520
I'm thoroughly enjoying
myself, so please.

00:46:11.520 --> 00:46:13.920
SPEAKER: Well, I think we
can wrap it up for now,

00:46:13.920 --> 00:46:15.360
but thanks again for coming.

00:46:15.360 --> 00:46:18.300
And I hope everyone
reads and enjoys

00:46:18.300 --> 00:46:19.857
and takes lessons of the book.

00:46:19.857 --> 00:46:20.940
JACK NOLAN: Thank you all.

00:46:20.940 --> 00:46:21.940
It's been an honor.

00:46:21.940 --> 00:46:24.390
[APPLAUSE]

